		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"PODCAST: What are we going to do about all these dead malls?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:95:"http://www.urbanindy.com/2016/01/28/podcast-what-are-we-going-to-do-about-all-these-dead-malls/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:104:"http://www.urbanindy.com/2016/01/28/podcast-what-are-we-going-to-do-about-all-these-dead-malls/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 28 Jan 2016 13:04:50 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Neighborhoods";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Downtown";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"redevelopment";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"http://www.urbanindy.com/?p=5621";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:127:"It's time to talk about the struggling mall typology in light of all the closures at Indianapolis' downtown Circle Centre Mall.";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Eric McAfee";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2432:"<p>This latest post&#8211;a podcast actually&#8211;is already over a week old, which would make it pretty stale by blogosphere terms, except that it&#8217;s particularly relevant for Urban Indy, in the wake of all the closures at the Circle Centre Mall (the most recent of which <a href="http://www.ibj.com/articles/56846-update-abercrombie-fitch-closes-local-stores">seems to be Abercrombie and Fitch</a>, though I wouldn&#8217;t hold my breath for yet another closure before February).</p>
<p>At any rate, this latest podcast has Aaron Renn of The Urbanophile interviewing me about my experience with this formerly ironclad retail typology.  No new malls have been built in a decade, and virtually all downtown malls in urban centers of mid-sized cities have closed; Indy&#8217;s Circle Centre is one of the last holdouts.  And the mall is failing even after tremendous investment in housing, including a 28-story apartment tower going up just a few blocks to the east.  Worst of all&#8211;there doesn&#8217;t seem to be another retail building typology to take its place.  Lifestyle centers, outlet malls, festival market places&#8211;while many are successful, none have proven a panacea for the ailing shopping culture.</p>
<div id="attachment_5622" style="width: 510px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img class="wp-image-5622 size-medium" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/IMG_2842-500x375.jpg" alt="IMG_2842" width="500" height="375" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/IMG_2842-500x375.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/IMG_2842.jpg 640w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /><p class="wp-caption-text">The food court at the Steamtown Mall in Scranton, PA.</p></div>
<p>So, what are we to do with all this space?  Clearly we can focus on the many malls&#8211;mostly upscale&#8211;that are still succeeding, or we can dwell on what type storefront uses are flourishing.  But these hulking, windowless department store shells offer a challenge for civic leadership, just as much as the revived downtown department store (aka Carson&#8217;s in Indianapolis) may also soon be a thing of the past.  Please check out the podcast, and we encourage comments as always.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s the <a href="http://www.urbanophile.com/2016/01/23/what-are-we-going-to-do-about-all-these-dead-malls/">link to the podcast</a>.  Enjoy!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
