nd the canal [&#8230;]";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Kevin Kastner";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4455:"<p>The second phase for the 9 on Canal project has been released to the <a href="http://www.indy.gov/eGov/City/DMD/Planning/Zoning/Documents/2016_documents/RC_HE_2016/1-28-16rc_he.pdf">Regional Center Hearing Examiner</a>, and are shown below.  These are designed to be geared towards college students at IUPUI, and it does add another retail presence on the canal. This has been a tricky proposition in the past, and the canal is getting close to a full build-out. In addition to the proposed <a href="http://www.indy.gov/eGov/City/DMD/Planning/Zoning/Documents/2016_documents/RC_HE_2016/1-14-16rc_he.pdf">canal playscape</a>, it does appear that at least the newer additions to the canal may help it start to be more than a mere <a href="http://www.urbanophile.com/2009/09/13/indy-the-failure-of-the-canal-walk/">office park amenity</a>.</p>
<p>The first image shows that the building is currently industrial, so adding more housing to this area is a good thing:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal1.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5612"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5612" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal1-500x418.jpg" alt="canal1" width="500" height="418" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal1-500x418.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal1.jpg 734w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal2.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5613"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5613" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal2-500x309.jpg" alt="canal2" width="500" height="309" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal2-500x309.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal2-768x475.jpg 768w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal2-1024x633.jpg 1024w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal2.jpg 1384w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal3.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5614"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5614" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal3-500x318.jpg" alt="canal3" width="500" height="318" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal3-500x318.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal3-768x489.jpg 768w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal3-1024x652.jpg 1024w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal3.jpg 1386w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a></p>
<p>There is an elevated walkway between the first and second phase, which isn&#8217;t exciting to see. The canal-level interface could probably use more glass or options for public interface:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal4.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5615"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5615" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal4-500x320.jpg" alt="canal4" width="500" height="320" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal4-500x320.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal4-768x492.jpg 768w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal4-1024x656.jpg 1024w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal4.jpg 1382w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal5.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5616"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5616" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal5-500x321.jpg" alt="canal5" width="500" height="321" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal5-500x321.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal5-768x493.jpg 768w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal5-1024x658.jpg 1024w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/canal5.jpg 1384w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a></p>
<p>There are still about 3-4 parcels left on the canal for development, so it&#8217;s possible they&#8217;ll all be developed within the next decade. The canal will never reach San Antonio&#8217;s level, but hopefully it will be more than a public afterthought.</p>
