ta";s:13:"Kevin Kastner";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4516:"<p>Recently, the Indianapolis Business Journal&#8217;s <a href="http://www.ibj.com/blogs/11-north-of-96th/post/56484-pizzology-closes-in-village-of-west-clay">Hamilton County Blog</a> has posted about troubles for the Village of West Clay&#8217;s retail area. I&#8217;ve always been fascinated by this development, as it was the first greenfield development in Central Indiana that attempted to form a traditional town center under the guise of <a href="http://www.newurbanism.org/">New Urbanism</a>. Here&#8217;s the layout as seen on Google Maps:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5600"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5600" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-500x348.jpg" alt="west clay" width="500" height="348" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-500x348.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-768x534.jpg 768w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-1024x713.jpg 1024w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay.jpg 1187w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a></p>
<p>A google <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/@39.9727456,-86.1954169,3a,75y,277.36h,75.39t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sjyXNTBeBrP_J6fO2_LxSVA!2e0!7i13312!8i6656?hl=en">Street View capture</a> of the development&#8217;s downtown area shows what has been derided by critics as a &#8220;fake town.&#8221;</p>
<div id="attachment_5602" style="width: 510px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-1.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5602"><img class="wp-image-5602 size-medium" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-1-500x227.jpg" alt="west clay" width="500" height="227" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-1-500x227.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-1-768x349.jpg 768w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay-1-1024x465.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Image Credit: Google Street View</p></div>
<p>This is basically a case of getting some basics right (tree, sidewalk, and building placement for example) but missing out on the most important one: People are creatures of habit. There was an equal opportunity to build this downtown at the corner of Main and Town as there was to build a brand new one in a former cornfield:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay2.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-5599"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5599" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay2-500x348.jpg" alt="west clay2" width="500" height="348" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay2-500x348.jpg 500w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay2-768x534.jpg 768w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay2-1024x713.jpg 1024w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/west-clay2.jpg 1187w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a></p>
<p>To its credit, the IBJ&#8217;s blog mentions this glaring problem. Unfortunately for West Clay, it may be too late to change. The infrastructure is already there, well off of the main streets.</p>
<p>Green field development is still happening to this day. It&#8217;s survived high gas prices, a devastating recession, and mortgage crisis. It has survived nascent urban revitalization in Indianapolis as well. As long as <a href="https://www.google.com/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=federal+government+suburbanization">suburbanisation is incentivized</a>, it will remain a part of future development. So at least in this case it might be done in a way where a person can take a useful walk.</p>
<p>West Clay&#8217;s version of new Urbanism was basically the local development community&#8217;s first attempt at admitting that some mistakes had been made with regards to street design. I hope that future green field developers will build from the inside out, incrementally from the traditional corners of the established road network. Urban Indy still will still prefer urban revitalization over green field development for a host of reasons, but at least it would stand a better chance of being a financially sustainable development.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
