ative: To increase safety for bicyclists. [&#8230;]";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Kevin Kastner";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5274:"<p>Much has been made in the media recently about the new configuration of Pennsylvania Street between St. Clair and Washington. Some of it has been <a href="http://www.indystar.com/story/news/2015/11/30/whats-deal-those-funky-new-bike-lanes-pennsylvania-street-downtown/76339714/">informative</a>, and some <a href="http://www.ibj.com/articles/55766-morris-downtown-no-longer-good-for-cars">hasn&#8217;t</a>.  It&#8217;s a good idea at this time to take a step back and reflect on the main goal of the initiative: To increase safety for bicyclists.</p>
<p>Partially because of the backlash, I decided to wait until they were closer to being finished to write a post on these lanes. There still may be a little bit of work left to do, but they are close enough now that the improvement is getting more obvious:</p>
<div id="attachment_5573" style="width: 291px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0309.jpg"><img class="wp-image-5573 size-medium" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0309-281x500.jpg" alt="IMAG0309" width="281" height="500" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0309-281x500.jpg 281w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0309-576x1024.jpg 576w" sizes="(max-width: 281px) 100vw, 281px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">All images credit: Kevin Kastner</p></div>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0304.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5574" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0304-281x500.jpg" alt="IMAG0304" width="281" height="500" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0304-281x500.jpg 281w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0304-576x1024.jpg 576w" sizes="(max-width: 281px) 100vw, 281px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0307.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5575" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0307-281x500.jpg" alt="IMAG0307" width="281" height="500" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0307-281x500.jpg 281w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0307-576x1024.jpg 576w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0307.jpg 1461w" sizes="(max-width: 281px) 100vw, 281px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0308.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5576" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0308-281x500.jpg" alt="IMAG0308" width="281" height="500" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0308-281x500.jpg 281w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0308-576x1024.jpg 576w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/IMAG0308.jpg 1588w" sizes="(max-width: 281px) 100vw, 281px" /></a></p>
<p>Here are <a href="https://indycog.org/news/2015/november/pennsylvania-bike-lanes--latest-info">some pdfs </a> that help describe the new configuration, courtesy of <a href="http://indycog.org/">IndyCog</a> and Sustain Indy:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn3.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5549" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn3-381x500.jpg" alt="penn3" width="381" height="500" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn3-381x500.jpg 381w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn3.jpg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 381px) 100vw, 381px" /></a> <a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5550" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn1-378x500.jpg" alt="penn1" width="378" height="500" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn1-378x500.jpg 378w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn1.jpg 654w" sizes="(max-width: 378px) 100vw, 378px" /></a> <a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-5551" src="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn2-374x500.jpg" alt="penn2" width="374" height="500" srcset="http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn2-374x500.jpg 374w, http://www.urbanindy.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/penn2.jpg 646w" sizes="(max-width: 374px) 100vw, 374px" /></a></p>
<p>In addition, IndyCog is hosting an <a href="http://indycog.org/news/2015/november/penn-street-separated-bike-lane-awareness-ride">awareness ride</a> on Friday, December 4th at 8 am. The ride starts at the Indianapolis Public Library and continues down Penn towards Washington Street.</p>
<p>About the only downside for this new bike lane is that it will make most of the other ones in the city look inferior. Also, the lanes start at St. Clair Street, which does not have a connecting cycle path. These are good problems to have.</p>
<p>This helping to lead the path forward for cycling in Indianapolis. I can&#8217;t wait to see the <a href="http://www.urbanindy.com/2015/02/25/new-yorkmichigan-street-protected-bike-lanes/">next initiative</a> on the near east side.</p>
